Objective

  1. The goal of this challenge is to explore this data to uncover findings that would help the Organizers create high quality events and sell more tickets.

  2. My aim was to do some data exploration to understand the data properly, and then move to modeling.

  3. I developed a plan to predict the Orders, as it is important to understand the top drivers that tends the users to place more orders.

This code consists of the following:

  1. Data Exploration

  2. Data Visualization

  3. Features construction

  4. Data selection and Manipulation

  5. Data preparation for Modeling

  6. Data partioning - 75% for training and 25% for testing

  7. Linear regression model

  8. Neural networks model

  9. Decision trees

  10. Model evaluation

  11. Future work and recommendations to product team.

Features construction

  1. time2publish = event_publish_date-signup_date (in days)

  2. days2start_event= event_publish_date- event_start_date (in days)

  3. published_wday = week day of event_publish_date

  4. published_month= month of event_publish_date

  5. event_published_hour = hour of event_publish_date (in hours)

  6. wday_of_event = weekday of event_start_date

  7. month_of_event = month of event_start_date

  8. event_hour = hour of event_start_date

  9. event_duration = event_end_date - event_start_date (in hours)

# Creating a new feature called time2publish(days)= event_publish_date-signup_date

raw_data$time2publish <- difftime(as.Date(raw_data$event_publish_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),as.Date(raw_data$signup_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),units="days")

# Creating a new variable called time2start_event = event_publish_date- event_start_date

raw_data$days2start_event <- difftime(as.Date(raw_data$event_start_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),as.Date(raw_data$event_publish_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),units="days")

# to find the best week of the day to publish an event

library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date
raw_data$published_wday <- wday(as.Date(raw_data$event_publish_date),label=TRUE)

#to find the best month to publish an event

raw_data$published_month<- month(as.Date(raw_data$event_publish_date))

#  hour of the day to publish an event

raw_data$event_published_hour<- hour(as.POSIXct(raw_data$event_publish_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"))
  

# week of the day to hold an event

raw_data$wday_of_event <- wday(as.Date(raw_data$event_start_date),label = TRUE)


#  month of the day to hold an event

raw_data$month_of_event <- month(as.Date(raw_data$event_start_date))

#  hour of the day to hold an event

raw_data$event_hour<- hour(as.POSIXct(raw_data$event_start_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"))


# event duration
raw_data$event_duration<-difftime(as.POSIXct(raw_data$event_end_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),as.POSIXct(raw_data$event_start_date,format= "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"),units="hours")

Currency conversions and calculations - to standardize all the other currency to USD.
currency.table<-read.csv("/Users/rameshthulasiram/Documents/Data_Interview_Challenge/eventbrite/Forex20Oct2016.csv")  # from the website- http://www.x-rates.com/table/?from=USD&amount=1
toUSD <- function(amount, code){
  amount <- as.numeric(as.character(amount))
  
  code <- as.character(code)
  
  matching <- as.character(currency.table$Code)==code
  
  forex_units <- currency.table[matching,]$USD.1.Unit
  return ( amount * as.numeric(as.character(forex_units)))
}

row.func <- function(x){
  return(toUSD(x[["revenue"]], x[["currency"]]))
}

revenue_USD<-apply(raw_data,1,row.func)

data_USD<-cbind(raw_data,revenue_USD)

write.csv(data_USD,file="data_usd.csv")

Predictive Modeling:

My idea is to predict the Orders and understand the factors influencing getting more orders. I chose to predict this over revenue because, the goal of this challenge is to help our organizers create high quality events. So I thought it is important to understand the top drivers that tends the users to place more orders.

Target variable: orders (continous value)

Independent Variable:

  1. category

  2. capacity

  3. time2publish = (event_publish_date-signup_date)

  4. days2start_event= event_publish_date- event_start_date (in days)

  5. published_wday = week day of event_publish_date

  6. published_month= month of event_publish_date

  7. event_published_hour = hour of event_publish_date (in hours)

  8. wday_of_event = weekday of event_start_date

  9. month_of_event = month of event_start_date

  10. event_hour = hour of event_start_date

  11. event_duration = event_end_date - event_start_date (in hours)

Data Preparation for Modeling

#target variable - orders

# independent variable - category, capacity, time2publish_1stevent, days2start_event, published_wday,published_month,event_published_hour,wday_of_event,month_of_event,event_hour,event_duration


# The orders column is very skewed, hence log transformation is taken to remove the skewness in the data. 

data_USD$log_orders<- log(data_USD$orders)

data_USD$scaled_orders <- scale(data_USD$orders)

data_USD$scaled_revenue <- scale(data_USD$revenue_USD)

data_USD<- data_USD[complete.cases(data_USD),]

## Partitioning Data into Train and Test datasets in 75:25
## 75% of the sample size
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(data_USD))

## set the seed to make your partition reproductible
set.seed(123)
train_ind<- sample(seq_len(nrow(data_USD)),replace=FALSE,size = smp_size)


train.base <- data_USD[train_ind, ]
test.base <- data_USD[-train_ind, ]

Linear Regression Model

  1. The output variable is continous and we are interested in finding the relationships between the independent variables and the target variable, hence linear regression is one of the simple models to start with.

  2. It is a statistical technique that allows us to predict one variable on the basis of several other variables.

frmla<- scaled_orders ~ category+capacity+days2start_event+ published_wday+published_month+event_published_hour+wday_of_event+month_of_event+event_hour+event_duration


lm.model <- lm(frmla, data=train.base)
summary(lm.model)

This model performs very poorly and the Adjusted R-squared is 0.0018.Even though the target variable is scaled, the model is not able to perform so well. Hence, this model can be rejected.

Since the regression model did not work well, I tried to discretize the target variable orders and see if that helps. This variable orders is very skewed so scaled that variable and then split into 3 equal groups. I did not want to coerce the outliers or throw the outliers, so I thought binning might help.

  1. Low Participation- Bin1 : [ 1, 5) - 33%
  2. Medium Participation- Bin2: [ 5, 20) - 33%
  3. High Participation- Bin3 : [20,77401] - 33%

Neural Network Model

  1. the output variable is categorical with 3 categories.

  2. neural network does not make assumptions about the underlying distribution of data and can model complex, non-linear functions & decision surfaces

  3. It is also very flexible with respect to missing and noisy values.

library(nnet)

set.seed(1234832)

formula<- new_orders_cat  ~ category+capacity+days2start_event+ published_wday+published_month+event_published_hour+wday_of_event+month_of_event+event_hour+event_duration

train1.nnet<-nnet(formula,train.base,size=3,rang=0.07,Hess=FALSE,decay=15e-4,maxit=250)

Decision Tree Model

  1. It is a non-linear classifier and can be used to model even complex decision surfaces.

  2. The aim is to clasify observations based on the nominal target. Hence, I chose to use this decision tree model to build a classification tree and also compare its performance with neural networks.

library(rpart)

library(rpart.plot)             # Enhanced tree plots

 
treemodel<- rpart(formula, data=train.base,method = "class",control=rpart.control(minsplit=742,cp=0.01) )

Future work:

  1. The accuracy of the predictive model can be improved if some more additional variables about the organizer and event are available (like price, venue location, ticket class etc.), inorder to predict orders.

  2. I tried to bin the target variable using different options and see if the model performance improves, but havent tried all the possible approaches. There are many options to this binning : quartile, quintile, decile, equal width binning, frequence binning etc. All these appoaches can be tried to build meaningful categories of orders and also see if the there is some improvement in the performance.

  3. Price of the order can be found = ( revenue in usd / no. of orders ), and predict price to sell their tickets at and also increase their likelihood of selling-out.

  4. Gross events revenue which is equal to sum of all the transactions made by a particular organizer, can be used to find how much value each organizer brings to event brite. This Gross events revenue can be measured for a month or year.

  5. Unsupervised learning techniques like clustering can be used to see if there is any natural groupings in the data and also classify the individuals in the data into smaller groups of similar individuals so that we can study each group.

Recommendations to the product team:

  1. The predictive model to predict orders category can be used to get an idea of the number of orders in advance.

  2. The important drivers as per the model are event_duration, days2start_event, category, event_hour, wday_of_event etc.

Example of a Rule: If event_duration < 1.066667 and days2start_event < 6.5, then predicted class= 1

This implies that when the event is published well in advance before the event start date, event duration, the category of the event, event hour and weekday of the event have effects on the number of the orders placed. Hence, by using these insights, high quality events can be created by organizers by planning well in advance.

It is also important to note that the model accuracy tells us there may be other factors, that impacts the order category.

  1. There is decresing trend in signups year- over - year. Also, from the day of month- sign up trend graph, it is clear that signups are more in the beginning of the month, so acquisition campaigns can be scheduled accordingly.

  2. Although there is decrease in signups, the orders and revenue are increasing year-over- year. There might be a good correlation between eventbrite good customer service support and this increasing trend of revenue.

  3. The time to publish their first event after signup graph, tells us that nearly 20% publish their events immediately after signup and 40% within a week. If the users dont organize anything after signup, may be some targeting ads (which emphasizes on eventbrite targeted support) may be sent to encourage them to organize an event.

  4. The number of events organized peaks during the months of September and October.

  5. Music seems to be favourite category for the organizers and users, as they pull in more crowd and also generate more revenue. So Music, Business and charity Organizers would bring in more revenue to eventbrite as well.

  6. The number of orders peaks when the event duration is 2 hours, so organizers can use this information to decide their event duration time. Shorter events ( less than 2 hours) and longer events (more than 2 hours) are mostly not attendees favourites.

  7. Best week of the day to hold an event is either Friday or Saturday. And, Monday brings in the least crowd. Organizers can use this information to decide upon the week of the day to hold an event.

  8. Best time of the day to hold an event is 6pm, since the revenue and orders peaks at 6pm.

It is important to note that the recommendations that I have given here are based on the visualization on this particular set of data and these trends that I see might have occured due to a random chance, hence it is important to test its statistical significance before implementing them.
